In C++, the following:<p><pre><code>  &quot;Hello, World!&quot;
</code></pre>
…is a null terminated <i>array of chars</i>.  When literal strings are not, in fact, strings, this is a problem with the language.  It&#x27;s <i>confusing</i>, you see?  Underlying semantics nonwithstanding, how on Earth the followig works:<p><pre><code>   (std::string)&quot;foo&quot; == &quot;foo&quot;
</code></pre>
and the following may not?!<p><pre><code>   &quot;foo&quot; == &quot;foo&quot;
</code></pre>
These are not basic concepts.  These are <i>trivia</i>.  I know there are reasons for these confusing rules, but they&#x27;re still confusing.  You should not mock the programmer for forgetting them now and then.
